headline: An Elusive Morris vs. a Cunning Jordan
content:
LEAD: As the free safety, he has the best view of the play. He sees everything, but with one possible exception when his team plays the Giants, and that's what worries Curtis Jordan of the Washington Redskins.
As the free safety, he has the best view of the play. He sees everything, but with one possible exception when his team plays the Giants, and that's what worries Curtis Jordan of the Washington Redskins.
It's Joe Morris. Jordan sometimes loses him in the forest of linemen and linebackers. Then, when he squirts through, it's sometimes too late.
''A lot of times, I just can't see him,'' Jordan said today as the Redskins began practicing for their encounter Sunday with the Giants in the National Conference championship game. ''You've got guys 6-5 and 6-6 blocking for him and guys 6-5 and 6-6 they're blocking on. All of a sudden, he pops out of nowhere.''
All that popping is a major concern to a free safety in run support. Often, he's the last line of defense if a back has cleared the linebackers. That can be dangerous with a player like Jordan. Just say his main attributes are cunning and strength, rather than speed and quickness. Speed Is Not His Strength
When Eric Dickerson of the Rams burst into the secondary for a 65-yard gain in the Redskins' 19-7 victory in the wild-card game, it was not Jordan who ran him down. It was Darrell Green, the little cornerback.
''When I saw them,'' Jordan said, ''I figured I could go out and get a hot dog.''
Yet Dickerson or even Walter Payton, whose Bears the Redskins beat last Saturday in the divisional round, 27-13, do not cause Jordan as much concern as Morris, he said. Dickerson is 6 feet 5 inches tall. Payton is 5-10. Morris is 5-7. Worse yet, Jordan said, Morris is more dangerous for a defense on the kind of artificial turf that hugs the floor of Giants Stadium. When the Giants beat the Redskins there this season, on the Monday night the Mets won the World Series, Morris ran 31 times for 181 yards, an average of 5.8 yards per carry. In the rematch six weeks later, on the spongy grass of R.F.K. Stadium in Washington, a 24-14 Giants victory, Morris carried 22 times for 62 yards, a 2.8 yard average.
''He's twice as effective on turf as grass,'' Jordan said. ''Turf suits his style. He has great bursts and real defined cuts. He had trouble when they were out on Frisco'' - Morris ran 13 times for 14 yards in the Giants' 21-17 victory in San Francisco - ''and he had trouble here. But he just killed us up there. I wish I'd have gone to the World Series instead of playing. But I couldn't get a ticket.'' Weather Could Be Factor
Another problem for Jordan could be the weather. Included in the forecast is the possibility of rain or snow. That could make the field slick, and wet turf could help the running back.
''He knows where he's going,'' Jordan said. ''He can also gauge his speed to make his cuts. If the field is wet, that favors them. If there's snow, it's anybody's game, although I think the team with the best running game is going to win.''
Jordan is a 10-year veteran who began his professional career as an original Tampa Bay Buccaneer in 1976 when they failed to win a game. He was waived shortly before the end of the 1981 season, and the Redskins signed him. He won a starting job in 1983 and has been there ever since.
He is something of an anomaly among the Redskins, a team in short supply of what Coach Joe Gibbs calls ''the flashy-type personality.'' He wears a small diamond stud earring in his left ear lobe and he is not afraid to speak his mind, even if it occasionally gets him in trouble. He has long, shaggy hair that sometimes sticks out of the back of his helmet and a scraggly reddish beard. First Met in 1978
Gibbs, who is clean-shaven and does not wear an earring, first encountered Jordan in 1978, when he was the Buccaneers' offensive coordinator. ''Oddly enough,'' he said, ''I remember his personality as being different then. He was more of a straight-lime type. Now, I would describe him as a free spirit.''
This will be Jordan's fourth N.F.C. championship game. The Buccaneers lost to the Rams in 1979, 9-0 - ''when Coach McKay wouldn't throw a pass if his life depended on it'' - and he was with the Redskins when they beat the Cowboys, 31-17, in the 1982 season and the 49ers, 24-21, in the 1983 season.
''Imagine, I played on one of the worst teams in football and in two Super Bowls,'' he said. If he keeps an eye on Morris, it could be three.
THE GIANTS VS. THE REDSKINS
